<h2 id="guidelines">Guidelines</h2>
<h3 id="form">Standalone or form</h3>
<p>A switch can be used on its own or more commonly as a list of options in a form, like this:</p>
<code-sample>
  <m-box style="width: 300px">
    <h4 class="mar-t-xs">Network settings</h4>
    <form>
      <fieldset class="flex justify-content-between align-items-center">
        <label>Wi-Fi</label>
        <input type="checkbox" is="switch" name="wifi" checked>
      </fieldset>
      <fieldset class="flex justify-content-between align-items-center">
        <label>Bluetooth</label>
        <input type="checkbox" is="switch" name="bluetooth" checked>
      </fieldset>
      <fieldset class="flex justify-content-between align-items-center">
        <label>Cellular</label>
        <input type="checkbox" is="switch" name="cellular">
      </fieldset>
      <fieldset class="flex flx-wrap justify-content-between align-items-center">
        <label>Personal Hotspot</label>
        <input type="checkbox" is="switch" name="hotspot" disabled>
        <small class="full-width">Currently unavailable</small>
      </fieldset>
    </form>
  </m-box>
</code-sample>
<h3 id="a11y">Accessibility</h3>
<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Roles/checkbox_role" target="_blank">MDN</a> says, "The first rule of ARIA is if a native HTML element or attribute has the semantics and behavior you require, use it instead of re-purposing an element and adding ARIA. Instead use the native HTML checkbox of <code>&lt;input type="checkbox"&gt;</code>, which natively provides all the functionality required."</p>
